> CH is not a fast combat healing spell.  I don't know anyone in their right mind who'd consider a casting time of 10 seconds "fast."  He was talking about small direct healing, IE remedy.  3-4 second casting times for hundreds of points of life, not 10 second for 10k.<br>
<br>
Everyone gets sense heading, which is why he didn't add it in.  True north is pretty stupid to have in there, but not everyone gets it, so I can see why you might possibly momentarily consider thinking about putting it in the list. <p>--------------------------<br><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=99855>Aeler</a>, 54th Cleric<br><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=99218>Teuvan</a>, 47th Bard</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utudamorf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tudamorf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elder Hierophant<br><center>of The Grove</center></span><br>  Posts: 2004<br> <font color=#333399>(7/22/02 2:24:23 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovegeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27894.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.geocities.com/lag999/rtfm.txt width=100 height=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Crunching</span><hr size=1> I took Thott's original chart and modified it to address the concerns I raised.  I added a "weight" to each ability to reflect both the usefulness of the ability and to compensate for abilities which are useful but broken down into many little categories (such as each statistic buff).  I also changed the categories a little bit and added a couple to reflect changes made in the game since the time of the original chart.<br>
<br>
The idea here was to try to derive a number for the <b>USEFUL VERSATILITY</b> of the class.  A class with a high result has many <b>useful</b> abilities.  A class with a low result does not have many useful abilities.  Having many useful abilities (or very few) does not mean the class is over (or under) balanced, but it does address the "jack of all trades" argument.<br>
<br>
Here we go:<br>
