Guess who's on top.  <img src=http://www.geocities.com/lag999/biggrin.txt> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utudamorf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tudamorf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elder Hierophant<br><center>of The Grove</center></span><br>  Posts: 2005<br> <font color=#333399>(7/22/02 2:50:57 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovegeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27894.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.geocities.com/lag999/rtfm.txt width=100 height=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Crunching</span><hr size=1> <b><i>Winged Death is 18% more damage per mana than Moonfire (including SCF III)</b></i><br>
<br>
Assuming, of course,:<br>
<br>
1.  The target is stationary (rooted).<br>
2.  The DoT lasts for its full duration.<br>
<br>
In a real-world example, the target might be moving for 2 ticks and you lose 2 ticks of the duration, reducing winged death damage to 75% of its theoretical maximum, and making it less efficient than moonfire.<br>
<br>
You are also assuming that the effect of specialization is identical.  In the real world, no druid specializes in conjuration (I would hope).  If that druid is specialized in evocation and has spell casting mastery 3, they use 21% less mana on nukes but only 13% less mana on swarm spells.<br>
<br>
That means, even assuming the theoretical example where the target is stationary and the DoT lasts for full duration:<br>
<br>
Moonfire is 1231 damage for 253 mana (4.87 damage/mana)<br>
Winged Death is 1560 damage for 305 mana (5.11 damage/mana)<br>
<br>
Making Winged Death only 5% more mana efficient.<br>
<br>
<b><i>and generates less aggro as a happy side effect.</b></i><br>
<br>
