 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utudamorf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tudamorf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elder Hierophant<br><center>of The Grove</center></span><br>  Posts: 2006<br> <font color=#333399>(7/22/02 3:44:04 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovegeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27894.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.geocities.com/lag999/rtfm.txt width=100 height=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Crunching</span><hr size=1> On the chart there's "group gate", "translocate," and "gate to safe spot" (succor), giving gate ability a fairly heavy weight.  Also I gave self mana regen a low figure because generally, in the scheme of things, a caster's self-only mana regen is very small when compared to meditation, horses, AAXP regen, flowing thought, etc.<br>
<br>
I do realize the categories are nowhere near perfect.  But all I did was take Thott's chart and make a small number of corrections/additions that were begging to be made (e.g., addition of Complete Healing as a primary ability), so most of the chart is legacy material.<br>
<br>
Reasonable minds will differ as to the weight values.  You might think gating is an 8 whereas another poster will give it a 4.  But most of us will agree in the crudest sense that, for example, complete healing deserves a 10 (highest value) and true north deserves a 0.1 (lowest value).  My point in creating the chart was to put <i>some</i> weight in there, because in the previous chart those two abilities (well, fast healing and true north) had the same value.<br>
<br>
If I had to specify general criteria, they would be:<br>
<br>
1.  If the ability is never or almost never used, 0.2 or less.<br>
2.  If the ability is sometimes used but either (a) has no significant impact on gameplay or (b) is highly situational, it gets 0.5 to 2.<br>
3.  If the ability is regularly used and somewhat affects gameplay, it gets a 2 to 5.<br>
4.  If the ability is a key element of the class, it gets a 5 to 9.<br>
5.  Abilities which constitute the "raison d'etre" of the class get a 10.<br>
<br>
Certainly you could embarrass me by finding examples where I broke my own rule, but you get the idea...<br>
<br>
Talyena says:  <b><i>and you will see pretty much the same four classes on top that you saw on the other one.</b></i><br>
<br>
In the original chart, the order (highest to lowest) was:<br>
<br>
1. ENC 2. SHM (tie) 3. BRD (tie) 4. DRU 5. NEC 6. RNG 7. SHD 8. CLR 9. MAG 10. WIZ 11. PAL 12. ROG 13. WAR (tie) 14. MNK (tie)<br>
<br>
In my chart, the order is:<br>
<br>
1. DRU 2. NEC 3. BRD 4. ENC 5. RNG 6. SHM 7. SHD 8. PAL 9. CLR 10. WIZ 11. MAG 12. ROG 13. MNK 14. WAR<br>
<br>
The top 4 classes are different, and some of the other classes shift position a lot.  For example, shamans had an inflated value in the original one because each individual statistic buff counted as an ability, whereas now they are 6th in useful versatility.<br>
<br>
And this chart places druids and necros on top in overall useful versatility, which I would conceptually think is the right answer given my past game experience.<br>
<br>
