Torvonnilous<br></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uchronomis.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Chronomis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Might be Housebroken</span><br>  Posts: 245<br> <font color=#333399>(7/22/02 2:26:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovegeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27894.topic&index=32>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Crunching</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Also, people forget that twisting is a very real world limit to a bards versitility... I have yet to really see most bards be able to twist more then 3 songs at once. Yes, there are exceptions since I once saw a bard doing what looked like 4-5 but I am not sure. By comparison, a druid can cast many buffs that last for 60-90 minutes and then forget about them until the icon flashes.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I actually considered posting that in my response earlier.  It's an important consideration regarding bard abilities.  However, it's not as great a restriction as it might seem to a druid who knows next to nothing about bards might think.  Consider:<br>
<br>
What percentage of the time do most of the buffs a druid is using actually have an effect?  If the group is at full health, regen does nothing.  If the group isn't under attack, between pulls for example, increased AC does nothing.  If the group isn't getting hit by spells, increased resists do nothing.  The point here is that if a song does nothing in a given situation, the bard can simply switch to another one that does have an effect.  Buffs generally lack this flexibility.<br>
<br>
Most bard songs also cost no mana at all.  I would argue that this is the primary &quot;balance&quot; reason why they generally can't keep long duration buffs up on everyone.<br>
<br>
Also, take a good look some time at bard songs.  Many more of them are multi-effect than other caster's spells.  So while they may only be able to keep three songs going, they can often keep many more &quot;effects&quot; going at once.<br>
<br>
I'm not trying to bash bards here.  Far from it.  I'm just pointing out that being limited in the number of spells/songs you can keep active at once isn't necessarily as severe a limitation as it might appear to be at first glance.<br>
<br>
 - Chronomis<br>
